Trypanosomiasis? - Sri Lanka: RFI 990707004230
Trypanosomiasis? - Sri Lanka (03) 990711141955
[1
Date: Mon, 12 Jul 1999 10:43:43 -0400
From: Aravinda de Silva <Aravinda_deSilva@med.unc.edu>

I am intrigued by Professor Dupouy-Camet's suggestion that macaques may
serve as a host for trypanosomes which may cross over to humans. Together
with colleagues in Sri Lanka, I recently described an epizootic dengue virus
in eastern Sri Lanka among toque macaques (_Macaca sinica_).
Reference: Serological evidence for an epizootic dengue virus infecting
toque macaques at Polonnaruwa, Sri Lanka. A. de Silva, W. Dittus, P.
Amerasinghe and F. Amerasinghe. Am. J. Trop. Med. Hyg. (1999) 60
(2):300-306.
I still have some macaque serum samples in my freezer. If any one is
interested in attempting to isolate trypanosomes or testing for trypanosome
antibodies, I can send them some _M. sinica_ serum.
--
Aravinda de Silva, Ph.D.
Assistant Professor
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill
Department of Microbiology and Immunology
