[2
Date: Tue, 13 Jul 1999
From: Dr Mulkit Singh <micmulki@nus.edu.sg>
Via: Chan Yow Cheong <chanyowcheong@pacific.net.sg>
ProMED-mail Regional Moderator for Asia

There have been a few reports in the 1970s in Malaysia of trypanosomiasis
amongst the aboriginal population. It is believed that these were simian
trypanosomes and had a _T. cruzi_-like appearance. I suspect that the Sri
Lankan case is similarly acquired from animals and may well be from monkeys.
For the benefit of every one interested in this infection, I am including
the references for the above reports:
1. Dissanaike et al 1974. Trypanosome infections in Orang Aslis (aborigines)
in Malaysia. Trans.Roy. Soc. Trop. Med. Hyg. 68:494-495
2. Weinman D 1970. Trypanosomiasis in macaques and in Man in Malaysia.
S.E.A. J. Trop. Med. & Publ. Hlth. 1: 11-18
3. Weinman D 1972. _Trypanosoma cyclops_ n sp, a pigmented trypanosome from
the Malaysian primates, _Macaca nemestrina_ and _M. ira_. Trans. Roy. Soc.
Trop. Med. Hyg. 66: 628 (I may have got the page no. wrong!)
4. Else JG et al 1976. Further studies on trypanosomiasis in Orang Asli
(aborigines) in West Malaysia. Trans. Roy. Soc. Trop. Med. Hyg. 70: 170-171.
--
Dr Mulkit Singh
Department of Microbiology
National University of Singapore
<micmulki@nus.edu.sg>
